## Context
The 0200 PDF-content audit (`scripts/qa_pdf_content.py`, `make audit-pdf-content`)
found three files in `docs/articles/` that are **not PDFs at all** — they are HTML
documents (saved error/paywall pages) stored under a `.pdf` name. `file(1)` confirms
each is `HTML document`. The `test_cited_works_available.py` presence gate passes
(a file exists) but the work is unreadable and uncitable — the same defect class as
the Lepenies mis-download that motivated 0200, and worse for the two under *cited*
keys (a fabricated-in-effect citation).

This is human-in-loop work: re-acquire the correct PDFs (BibCNRS/EZproxy, publisher,
DOIfetch, Anna's Archive as last resort — see reference_paywalled_acquisition), verify
each against its copyright page, and drop it in over the broken file.

## The three files (from the 0200 audit, score -2 "<NOT A PDF: html>")
- `docs/articles/michaelowa2007.pdf` — **CITED**. bib title: "Climate or Development:
  Is ODA Diverted from Its Original Purpose?" (Michaelowa & Michaelowa).
- `docs/articles/stadelmann2011.pdf` — **CITED**. bib title: "New and Additional to
  What? Assessing Options for Baselines to Assess 'New and Additional' Climate Finance".
- `docs/articles/roberts2021.pdf` — uncited. bib title: "Rebooting a Failed Promise of
  Climate Finance". Lower priority (no manuscript hazard) but fix while here.

## Actions
1. Re-acquire each correct PDF; verify title/authors against the copyright page.
2. Replace the broken HTML files in `docs/articles/` (gitignored — not committed).
3. Re-run `make audit-pdf-content`; confirm the three no longer appear as "<NOT A PDF>".

## Verification
- [ ] `file docs/articles/{michaelowa2007,stadelmann2011,roberts2021}.pdf` → each "PDF document".
- [ ] `make audit-pdf-content` shows 0 "<NOT A PDF>" rows.
- [ ] michaelowa2007 + stadelmann2011 content confirmed against copyright page.

## Exit criteria
- The two cited broken files (and, best-effort, roberts2021) are replaced with the
  correct works; the audit reports no not-a-PDF entries.
